        <bioghist id="ref4">
            <head>Biography</head>
            <p>A native of Lopez, Pennsylvania, Steven Stupak enitemed in the Army Air Corps on Jan 7, 1942, and served as a member of the 94th Bomber Group. While assigned to the 8th Air Force Base as a Flight Engineer he was a member of the 331st Bomber Squadron. Technical Sergeant Steven Stupak was shot down over Germany on October 7, 1944 and spent time in German and Polish Prisoner of War camps. For his bravery and courageous efforts during World War II, he received the Air Medal with one cluster, and the Purple Heart. Steven was discharged on Oct 14, 1945.</p>
        </bioghist>
        <scopecontent id="ref7">
            <head>Scope and Contents of the Collection</head>
            <p>This collection details Steven Stupak’s experiences as a Flight Engineer and Prisoner of War during World War II. A 97 minute taped interview was conducted on December 18, 2003 at Central Connecticut State University by Eileen Hurst. Along with Mr. Stupak’s taped interview the collection contains reproductions of scanned personal and military manuscripts, photographs, and correspondence dating from 1942 to 1945. These materials describe bombing missions, interactions between American and German service men, and conditions in German and Polish POW camps. Local news articles and publications from 2004 and 2005 document veteran recognition programs and observances in Connecticut.</p>
        </scopecontent>
